4. Aut instrui aut. sarcinas comgere] “Before the army was arrayed for fighting, or had (even) put the baggage toge- ther’' (as usual before action). Sarcina, the soldier's pack or bundle: Juvenal, ii. 103, speculum civilis sarcina belli.

5. Latrocinio proelio] This opposition is frequently employed. Comp. Liv. xxiX. 6, latrociniis magis quam justo bello gerebatur res. Cic, in Catil. i. 10.

It is explained, “the Romans being veterans and meruits, and on that account skilful in warfare‚'’ i.e. because they were not all recruits.
